<subSubSection lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,1954,2020]" lastBlockId="18.[151,1436,152,618]" lastPageId="18" lastPageNumber="19" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1954,1980]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species can be recognized by the elongate posterolateral projections of the pygophore in males, whereas all other known 
<collectingCountry box="[535,588,1994,2020]" name="Thailand" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Thai</collectingCountry>
congeners lack these posterolateral projections. Females of 
<taxonomicName box="[1303,1436,1994,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Eotrechus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kalidasa">
<emphasis box="[1303,1321,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1337,1436,1995,2020]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">kalidasa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be recognized by the length of the mesosternum less than twice as long as the metasternum (
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982 a) Semiterrestrial water striders of the genera Eotrechus Kirkaldy and Chimarrhometra Bianchi (Insecta, Hemiptera, Gerridae). Steenstrupia, 9, 1 - 25." type="journal article" year="1982" yearSuffix="a">
Andersen 
<number box="[151,213,192,218]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1982.0">1982</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
), whereas in all other known 
<collectingCountry box="[575,628,192,218]" name="Thailand" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Thai</collectingCountry>
congeners the mesosternum is at least twice as long as the metasternum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,152,618]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,336,271,297]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species was previously known only from 
<collectingCountry box="[887,947,272,298]" name="India" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">India</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1004,1122,272,298]" name="Myanmar" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
; thus this is the first record of 
<taxonomicName box="[182,315,312,338]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Eotrechus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kalidasa">
<emphasis box="[182,200,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[215,315,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">kalidasa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[386,490,312,338]" name="Thailand" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and the easternmost record of this species. A single, winged male specimen was collected from a malaise trap set over a small creek in a densely forested area in Phu Hin Rongkla NP. We sampled the creek four times in the last five years, but no specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[984,1102,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Eotrechus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[984,1102,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Eotrechus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected. Presumably, the specimen flew into the trap from a nearby unfavorable habitat, as it has been reported that several tropical species of 
<taxonomicName box="[278,380,472,498]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Gerridae</taxonomicName>
disperse throughout the year from unfavorable habitats to new habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Fernando" box="[1248,1431,472,498]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Fernando, CH. (1963) Notes on aquatic insects colonizing an isolated pond in Mawai, Johore. Bulletin of the National Museum, Singapore 32: 80 - 89." type="journal article" year="1963">
Fernando 
<number box="[1370,1431,472,498]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1963.0">1963</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Andersen" box="[151,349,512,538]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1982 b) Semiaquatic Bugs (Hemiptera, Gerromorpha). Phylogeny, Adaptations, Biogeography and Classification. Entomonograph, Vol. 3. Scandinavian Science Press, Klampenborg, Denmark, 455 pp." type="book" year="1982" yearSuffix="b">
Andersen 
<number box="[270,332,512,538]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1982.0">1982</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
